{"ts":"2026-06-26T08:44:48.118Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Analyzing Build Timeouts**\n\nI'm currently looking into the recent validation log. The next build succeeded, which is good, but my own build timed out. I realized the timeout is set at 30 seconds, and the next build runs around 25 seconds, meaning it's right on the edge. This explains the intermittent failures I've been seeing.\n\n\n**Investigating Recent Commits**\n\nI'm now diving into the latest commits to pinpoint potential causes for the build timeouts. I'm focusing on these specific files: `BentoGrid.tsx`, `ClientSuccessSection.tsx`, `JourneySection.tsx`, and `WhatWeBuildSection.tsx`. I'm starting by analyzing `ClientSuccessSection.tsx`, particularly lines 64-75, which relate to a card component. I'm seeking specific areas that could be resource-intensive.\n\n\n**Clarifying CSS Behavior**\n\nI've been examining the CSS `group` and `group-hover` classes. Initially, I thought that hovering over a `group` element would trigger its own `group-hover` styles. But I realize that `.group:hover` targets *descendants* with `group-hover` classes. To style the hovered `group` directly, I'll need to use standard `hover` states. I'm now testing the implications of this distinction in practice.\n\n\n**Confirming Tailwind Hover Behavior**\n\nI've confirmed the unexpected hover behavior. It turns out that applying `group-hover` to the same element as the `group` class doesn't trigger the hover effect. The issue stems from Tailwind's generation of descendant combinator rules, which require the `group-hover` styles to be applied to a child or descendant of the `group` element. I've verified this with the actual generated CSS and now need to see where this behavior exists in our code.\n\n\n**Verifying Hover States**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on the hover state of the cards. I confirmed that `group-hover` does *not* trigger on hover of the card, but `hover` does. I've corrected the `ClientSuccessSection.tsx` and the hover gradient is now working. I'm now checking `JourneySection.tsx` to ensure this behavior is correctly applied there. I'm also ensuring that these rules are actually necessary given the context of a link.\n\n\n**Refining Group Hover Logic**\n\nI've been further refining the hover logic, considering that the parent `Link` component has the `group` class, meaning its child `motion.div` can use `group-hover` styles. I'm now verifying if `group-hover` is the right choice for the `-translate-y-3` effect, particularly since the hover area of the `Link` and `motion.div` are essentially identical. I'm double-checking the code to see if there are other styling conflicts. I'm aiming for consistent behavior.\n\n\n"}}
